   EARNINGS: Foote, Cone &amp; Belding Communications, Chicago,
reported first-quarter net income fell 41% to $1.34 million,
or 13 cents a share, from $2.3 million, or 23 cents a share,
in the year-earlier period. Revenue dropped 7% to $72.2
million from $77.3 million in the first quarter of 1989.
Foote Cone said net was off in part because of lower income
from U.S. operations and interest expense relating to its
alliance with France's Publicis. The revenue drop, it said,
was due to the sale of its Golin/Harris public-relations
subsidiary.
                                                                                                       

   WHO'S NEWS: Bill Lane was named executive vice president
of JWT West, the arm that directs J. Walter Thompson's Los
Angeles and San Francisco operations. Mr. Lane was previously
co-executive creative director at the agency's New York
office. Jim Agnew, executive vice president and general
manager of Thompson's Los Angeles office, yesterday denied
industry reports that he plans to the leave the agency.
Thompson is a unit of WPP.
                                                                                                       

   ACQUISITION: D'Arcy Masius Benton &amp; Bowles, New York,
acquired a minority interest in Synergie Communications Ltd.,
Thailand. DMB&amp;B plans to merge its office there with
Synergie; the shop will be renamed Synergie/DMB&amp;B Ltd. Terms
weren't disclosed.
                                                                                                       

   NEW ACCOUNT: U S Sprint and Britain's Cable &amp; Wireless
named Chiat/Day/Mojo to handle the ad account for the
combined telecommunications firms' new Global Fon service.
Billings couldn't be determined.
